00:51:34.260 --> 00:51:34.880
Yeah, sure.

00:51:34.880 --> 00:51:36.130
AUDIENCE: Thanks for the talk.

00:51:36.130 --> 00:51:37.540
The foxes are adorable.

00:51:37.540 --> 00:51:40.960
I'm curious if they
tried to control

00:51:40.960 --> 00:51:47.170
for researcher's bias, like
would Lyudmila favor animals

00:51:47.170 --> 00:51:49.020
that have that domestication?

00:51:49.020 --> 00:51:51.020
LEE ALLEN DUGATKIN: Yeah,
it's a great question.

00:51:51.020 --> 00:51:55.635
Right, and so this is
an inherent problem

00:51:55.635 --> 00:51:57.010
in this kind of
experiment, where

00:51:57.010 --> 00:51:59.330
you're going to gauge behavior.

00:51:59.330 --> 00:52:03.310
So I think that, over the
course of the experiment,

00:52:03.310 --> 00:52:05.440
they've gotten much better
and tighter about this.

00:52:05.440 --> 00:52:08.600
Initially, like when I talked
about that place, Lesnoi,

00:52:08.600 --> 00:52:12.020
it was really Lyudmila
and Lyudmila alone.

00:52:12.020 --> 00:52:16.720
But once the experiment moved
in 1967 to the experimental farm

00:52:16.720 --> 00:52:18.340
and there was a
whole team of people,

00:52:18.340 --> 00:52:21.400
they began to do other
things that really

00:52:21.400 --> 00:52:24.050
controlled as much as possible
for what you're talking about,

00:52:24.050 --> 00:52:24.550
OK?

00:52:24.550 --> 00:52:26.793
So first of all, the
key thing they do

00:52:26.793 --> 00:52:28.210
is they've adopted
techniques that

00:52:28.210 --> 00:52:30.190
come from psychology
because psychologists

00:52:30.190 --> 00:52:31.660
have this problem all the time.

00:52:31.660 --> 00:52:33.368
You're measuring
behavior, and how do you

00:52:33.368 --> 00:52:35.800
know you're only using
what you think you are?

00:52:35.800 --> 00:52:37.780
Maybe you're being
affected by other things.

00:52:37.780 --> 00:52:41.980
The classic way to do this is to
have multiple different people

00:52:41.980 --> 00:52:46.270
independently assess whatever
is being looked at and then look

00:52:46.270 --> 00:52:50.230
for type correlations across
people in terms of who says

00:52:50.230 --> 00:52:51.830
the animal is friendly
and who isn't.

00:52:51.830 --> 00:52:53.920
And that's what they do now.

00:52:53.920 --> 00:52:56.370
The other thing that
they do is that there

00:52:56.370 --> 00:52:59.500
are many, many components
of behavior that they're

00:52:59.500 --> 00:53:02.650
looking for, not just the
four things that Lyudmila

00:53:02.650 --> 00:53:05.350
talked about early on.

00:53:05.350 --> 00:53:08.718
The core of it is they're
still looking for attributes

00:53:08.718 --> 00:53:10.510
of friendliness towards
humans, but they've

00:53:10.510 --> 00:53:13.870
subdivided that into
dozens of different things.

00:53:13.870 --> 00:53:17.370
So that plus the
multiple observers

00:53:17.370 --> 00:53:19.630
is the classic way to
handle this problem,

00:53:19.630 --> 00:53:21.687
and they do the best
they can with it.

00:53:21.687 --> 00:53:22.520
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:53:22.520 --> 00:53:25.075
LEE ALLEN DUGATKIN: Yeah.

