00:55:24.020 --> 00:55:26.060
was it sort of like
a similar timeline,

00:55:26.060 --> 00:55:27.420
or did it take much longer?

00:55:27.420 --> 00:55:28.795
LEE ALLEN DUGATKIN:
Yeah, I mean,

00:55:28.795 --> 00:55:30.990
so the mink too
breed once a year,

00:55:30.990 --> 00:55:33.260
and I think they
were beginning to see

00:55:33.260 --> 00:55:36.500
serious changes within a
couple of dozen generations

00:55:36.500 --> 00:55:37.790
like the foxes.

00:55:37.790 --> 00:55:40.640
Now, you have to remember
also that this is--

00:55:40.640 --> 00:55:42.050
I mean, it's hard
to say anything

00:55:42.050 --> 00:55:46.700
about the absolute
amount of time

00:55:46.700 --> 00:55:48.620
and how important that
is in the domestication

00:55:48.620 --> 00:55:51.650
process in the wild only
because this is really

00:55:51.650 --> 00:55:54.190
super intense selection.

00:55:54.190 --> 00:55:56.440
You know, you're just
using the top 10%.

00:55:56.440 --> 00:55:58.790
In evolutionary
history, our ancestors

00:55:58.790 --> 00:56:00.990
would not have been
doing that kind of thing.

00:56:00.990 --> 00:56:04.550
And initially, it would have
been unconscious selection--

00:56:04.550 --> 00:56:07.503
just sort of the ones that
came closest were the ones that

00:56:07.503 --> 00:56:08.670
were friendliest, and so on.

00:56:08.670 --> 00:56:10.040
Then, when they started
doing it consciously,

00:56:10.040 --> 00:56:11.665
it would not have
been to the intensity

00:56:11.665 --> 00:56:12.915
that we're talking about here.

00:56:12.915 --> 00:56:13.820
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:56:13.820 --> 00:56:16.530
LEE ALLEN DUGATKIN: Sure.

00:56:16.530 --> 00:56:18.480
AUDIENCE: So one
thing that you kept

00:56:18.480 --> 00:56:20.100
bringing up in this
presentation is

00:56:20.100 --> 00:56:24.930
that these specific domesticated
behaviors that these foxes

00:56:24.930 --> 00:56:28.497
acquire are dog-like behaviors.

00:56:28.497 --> 00:56:30.330
And I know that there
is some relationship--

00:56:30.330 --> 00:56:33.270
I'm not sure how close it is--

00:56:33.270 --> 00:56:37.590
but are there differences
between the two

00:56:37.590 --> 00:56:42.210
that still persist,
and how close are they

00:56:42.210 --> 00:56:46.020
really after domestication
in this form?

00:56:46.020 --> 00:56:47.550
LEE ALLEN DUGATKIN:
Well, I guess

00:56:47.550 --> 00:56:49.717
you can answer that at a
couple of different levels.

00:56:49.717 --> 00:56:52.110
First, they're both
canines, right?

00:56:52.110 --> 00:56:54.810
So they have a shared
evolutionary history.

00:56:54.810 --> 00:56:57.030
But their most recent
common ancestor

00:56:57.030 --> 00:56:58.870
was on the order of
12 million years ago.

00:56:58.870 --> 00:57:00.990
But they're all canines.

00:57:00.990 --> 00:57:03.840
I use the language
of "their behavior

00:57:03.840 --> 00:57:06.660
is very dog-like" as a
way to sort of put it

00:57:06.660 --> 00:57:10.230
in context, meaning they
lick hands, they wag tails,

00:57:10.230 --> 00:57:11.850
and so on.

00:57:11.850 --> 00:57:15.780
In that sense, they
are very dog-like,

00:57:15.780 --> 00:57:18.690
but in many, many other
ways, they are not.

00:57:18.690 --> 00:57:22.260
So they are not animals that
are inherently gregarious.

00:57:22.260 --> 00:57:25.020
They don't necessarily--
they're not animals

00:57:25.020 --> 00:57:27.090
that like to live in groups.

00:57:27.090 --> 00:57:30.870
There are many, many differences
between the domesticated foxes

00:57:30.870 --> 00:57:33.300
and dogs, but there
are a tremendous number

00:57:33.300 --> 00:57:36.450
of similarities that seem
to be due to choosing

00:57:36.450 --> 00:57:40.240
for this pro-social behavior.

00:57:40.240 --> 00:57:45.180
I mean, at the genetic level,
although the underlying changes

00:57:45.180 --> 00:57:47.460
like we talked about
have been similar,

00:57:47.460 --> 00:57:49.830
you couldn't breed them
or anything like that.

00:57:49.830 --> 00:57:50.880
AUDIENCE: Right.

00:57:50.880 --> 00:57:53.760
I guess, I don't
want to hold up,

00:57:53.760 --> 00:57:56.190
but I would have
also asked how far

00:57:56.190 --> 00:57:57.658
away are we from speciation?

00:57:57.658 --> 00:57:59.700
LEE ALLEN DUGATKIN: Yeah,
that's a good question.

00:57:59.700 --> 00:58:03.080
And the answer is
very far, I think.

00:58:03.080 --> 00:58:06.870
So the aggressive foxes
and the domesticated foxes

00:58:06.870 --> 00:58:08.093
can breed perfectly well.

00:58:08.093 --> 00:58:10.260
They do it all the time to
understand the underlying

00:58:10.260 --> 00:58:11.190
genetics.

00:58:11.190 --> 00:58:14.310
They've never attempted
anything with wild foxes

00:58:14.310 --> 00:58:17.010
because they're terrified
of introducing rabies

00:58:17.010 --> 00:58:18.160
and all this sort of thing.

00:58:18.160 --> 00:58:19.410
But there's no
reason in the world

00:58:19.410 --> 00:58:20.785
to think that they
wouldn't breed

00:58:20.785 --> 00:58:22.950
perfectly well with wild foxes.

00:58:22.950 --> 00:58:26.970
So, so far, there's not
reproductive barriers.

00:58:26.970 --> 00:58:30.270
But again, this is 60
years, which is nothing.

00:58:30.270 --> 00:58:32.970
If they ran the experiment
for another 500 years,

00:58:32.970 --> 00:58:34.860
would there be differences?

00:58:34.860 --> 00:58:35.490
Maybe.

00:58:35.490 --> 00:58:37.700
Even that's a small amount
of evolutionary time.

00:58:37.700 --> 00:58:38.921
But we don't know.

00:58:38.921 --> 00:58:39.754
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:58:39.754 --> 00:58:41.212
LEE ALLEN DUGATKIN:
You're welcome.

