00:59:49.550 --> 00:59:52.280
I wonder if she ever
exchanged any stories

00:59:52.280 --> 00:59:54.795
with you or any observations.

00:59:54.795 --> 00:59:57.170
LEE ALLEN DUGATKIN: So we do
talk about this a little bit

00:59:57.170 --> 00:59:57.980
in the book.

00:59:57.980 --> 00:59:59.270
So here is the short version.

01:00:03.440 --> 01:00:06.590
In the late '70s,
Belyaev, her mentor

01:00:06.590 --> 01:00:09.860
and the person who basically
was her go-to person

01:00:09.860 --> 01:00:14.300
on this experiment,
Belyaev hypothesized

01:00:14.300 --> 01:00:20.000
that human evolution was an
example of self-domestication.

01:00:20.000 --> 01:00:24.350
And the self-domestication
idea is this--

01:00:24.350 --> 01:00:30.110
instead of some external force
choosing the animals that

01:00:30.110 --> 01:00:34.070
are friendliest or calmest,
in self-domestication,

01:00:34.070 --> 01:00:35.760
that happens by mate choice.

01:00:35.760 --> 01:00:38.540
So the idea was, in
evolutionary history,

01:00:38.540 --> 01:00:40.070
both males and
females would have

01:00:40.070 --> 01:00:42.590
been more likely to
choose calmer, more

01:00:42.590 --> 01:00:46.020
cooperative mates, right,
for all sorts of reasons.

01:00:46.020 --> 01:00:49.970
First of all, interpersonal
aggression would be minimized.

01:00:49.970 --> 01:00:52.820
And also things that
require cooperation

01:00:52.820 --> 01:00:55.070
would have been maximized.

01:00:55.070 --> 01:00:57.440
And the argument,
then, is that, by doing

01:00:57.440 --> 01:01:01.130
that, by selecting the
calmest, friendliest mates,

01:01:01.130 --> 01:01:04.070
you are, in fact, mimicking
the process of domestication.

01:01:04.070 --> 01:01:05.870
It's just self-domestication.

01:01:05.870 --> 01:01:08.270
This was an idea that
Belyaev had in the late '70s.

01:01:08.270 --> 01:01:10.610
Didn't really do a lot with it.

01:01:10.610 --> 01:01:15.140
Just in the last three
months, Richard Wrangham,

01:01:15.140 --> 01:01:18.950
a colleague of mine at
Harvard, has an entire book out

01:01:18.950 --> 01:01:20.870
on human self-domestication.

01:01:20.870 --> 01:01:24.530
And now there's evidence
from all different fields

01:01:24.530 --> 01:01:28.550
to suggest that we may
very well be the product

01:01:28.550 --> 01:01:30.650
of self-domestication.

01:01:30.650 --> 01:01:33.810
And the evidence comes in
lots of different forms,

01:01:33.810 --> 01:01:38.060
one of which is that,
if you compare--

01:01:38.060 --> 01:01:41.030
oh, if you compare--

01:01:41.030 --> 01:01:42.200
it says, wrap up, please.

01:01:42.200 --> 01:01:42.700
I got it.

01:01:42.700 --> 01:01:46.490
OK, I'm ready to stop any
time you guys are, right?

01:01:46.490 --> 01:01:47.990
So you have to tell
me when to stop.

01:01:50.910 --> 01:01:56.030
So one of the forms is that, if
you compare us to our closest

01:01:56.030 --> 01:01:59.180
living relatives,
meaning chimpanzees,

01:01:59.180 --> 01:02:03.680
we tend to show traits that
are more in the domestication

01:02:03.680 --> 01:02:07.040
syndrome than
chimpanzees do, right?

01:02:07.040 --> 01:02:09.110
We have longer
reproductive periods,

01:02:09.110 --> 01:02:11.000
we have lower stress
hormone levels,

01:02:11.000 --> 01:02:14.210
we have many juvenilized
features compared

01:02:14.210 --> 01:02:16.460
to chimpanzees.

01:02:16.460 --> 01:02:18.500
And there are many
other forms of evidence

01:02:18.500 --> 01:02:22.130
to suggest that we have
self-domesticated ourselves.

01:02:22.130 --> 01:02:24.440
I would suggest, if
you're interested,

01:02:24.440 --> 01:02:28.920
Richard's book is called
"The Goodness Paradox,"

01:02:28.920 --> 01:02:29.830
and it just came out.

01:02:29.830 --> 01:02:31.170
It's getting a lot of attention.

01:02:31.170 --> 01:02:33.123
You could easily
find it on Amazon

01:02:33.123 --> 01:02:34.290
when you search for my book.

01:02:34.290 --> 01:02:35.720
So there you go.

01:02:35.720 --> 01:02:36.810
Thank you very much.

